Caching Strategy Guide for Headless WordPress + Next.js
WordPress Configuration (Production)
1. Enable These Caches
bash# Object Cache (already have Object Cache Pro)
wp plugin activate object-cache-pro

# REST API Caching
wp plugin install wp-rest-cache --activate
2. Configure Breeze Plugin

‚úÖ Enable: Database Query Cache
‚úÖ Enable: Object Cache
‚ùå Disable: HTML Minification (not needed)
‚ùå Disable: CSS/JS Minification (not needed)
‚úÖ Enable: Lazy Load (for admin panel only)

3. Varnish Configuration
Keep Varnish enabled for API endpoints:
nginx# In your Varnish config
if (req.url ~ "^/graphql" || req.url ~ "^/wp-json") {
    set req.backend_hint = default;
    return (pass); # Or cache with short TTL
}
Next.js Configuration
1. Image Optimization Setup
typescript// next.config.js
module.exports = {
  images: {
    domains: ['woocommerce-1475440-5585552.cloudwaysapps.com'],
    formats: ['image/avif', 'image/webp'],
    deviceSizes: [640, 750, 828, 1080, 1200, 1920, 2048, 3840],
    imageSizes: [16, 32, 48, 64, 96, 128, 256, 384],
  },
}
2. Product Page Caching Strategy
typescript// pages/products/[slug].tsx
export async function getStaticProps({ params }) {
  const product = await fetchProductBySlug(params.slug);

  return {
    props: { product },
    revalidate: 3600, // Revalidate every hour
  }
}

export async function getStaticPaths() {
  const products = await fetchAllProducts();

  return {
    paths: products.map(p => ({ params: { slug: p.slug } })),
    fallback: 'blocking', // Generate new products on-demand
  }
}
3. API Route Caching
typescript// pages/api/products.ts
export default async function handler(req, res) {
  res.setHeader(
    'Cache-Control',
    'public, s-maxage=300, stale-while-revalidate=600'
  );

  const products = await fetchProducts();
  res.json(products);
}
4. GraphQL Query Caching
typescript// lib/apollo-client.ts
import { ApolloClient, InMemoryCache } from '@apollo/client';

const client = new ApolloClient({
  uri: 'https://your-wordpress.com/graphql',
  cache: new InMemoryCache({
    typePolicies: {
      Product: {
        keyFields: ['id'],
        fields: {
          // Cache product images for 24 hours
          images: {
            merge: true,
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }),
  defaultOptions: {
    watchQuery: {
      fetchPolicy: 'cache-first',
    },
  },
});
Performance Best Practices
1. Image Loading Strategy
tsximport Image from 'next/image';

function ProductImage({ src, alt }) {
  return (
    <Image
      src={src}
      alt={alt}
      width={800}
      height={600}
      quality={85}
      placeholder="blur"
      blurDataURL={generateBlurDataURL()} // Generate base64 blur
      loading="lazy" // For below-fold images
      priority={false} // True for above-fold images
    />
  );
}
2. Static Generation for Heavy Pages
typescript// Generate at build time
export async function getStaticProps() {
  const [products, categories, featuredStones] = await Promise.all([
    fetchProducts({ limit: 50 }),
    fetchCategories(),
    fetchFeaturedStones(),
  ]);

  return {
    props: { products, categories, featuredStones },
    revalidate: 3600, // ISR: Regenerate every hour
  };
}
3. CDN Configuration (Optional)
If you want extra performance:
javascript// Use Cloudflare or similar CDN for WordPress uploads
const imageLoader = ({ src, width, quality }) => {
  return `https://cdn.your-domain.com/${src}?w=${width}&q=${quality || 75}`;
};

<Image loader={imageLoader} ... />
Monitoring & Testing
Performance Metrics to Track

Core Web Vitals

LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) < 2.5s
FID (First Input Delay) < 100ms
CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) < 0.1


API Performance

GraphQL query response time < 200ms
Image optimization time < 100ms
Cache hit rate > 80%



Testing Commands
bash# Test image optimization
curl -I https://your-next-app.com/_next/image?url=...

# Check cache headers
curl -I https://your-wordpress.com/graphql

# Lighthouse CI
npm install -g @lhci/cli
lhci autorun
Summary Checklist
WordPress (Production)

 Enable Object Cache Pro
 Configure REST API caching
 Set up Varnish for API endpoints
 Disable unnecessary Breeze features
 Consider CDN for wp-content/uploads

Next.js

 Configure next/image domains
 Implement getStaticProps with ISR
 Set up Apollo Client caching
 Use proper cache headers
 Implement blur placeholders
 Monitor Core Web Vitals

Don't Worry About

‚ùå WordPress page caching
‚ùå WordPress HTML/CSS/JS optimization
‚ùå WordPress lazy loading (except admin)
‚ùå Complex caching plugins

Remember: Next.js handles most of the heavy lifting for performance. Focus on:

Fast API responses from WordPress
Proper static generation in Next.js
Smart image optimization strategies

The combination of WordPress API caching + Next.js static generation will make your stone showroom site incredibly fast! üöÄ
